Description: # riscv-xray
        
        Developer-friendly RISC-V extension profiler. One command to see which RVA23 extensions your binary actually uses, with actionable compiler recommendations.
        
        ```
        $ riscv-xray profile ./my-service
        
          riscv-xray - profiling 'my-service'...
        
        ---------------------------------------------------------
          riscv-xray v0.1.0  Extension Usage Report
        ---------------------------------------------------------
          Binary:   my-service
          Backend:  riscv-xray-builtin
          Profile:  RVA23
        
          Extension Usage
          -------------------------------------------------------
          RVV    Vector           ████████████████  52.1%  [+]
          Zba    Address gen      ███░░░░░░░░░░░░░   7.7%  [~]
          Zbb    Bit manip        ██░░░░░░░░░░░░░░   3.3%  [~]
          Zbc    Carry-less mul   ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░   0.0%  [-]
          Zbkx   Crypto xbar      ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░   0.0%  [-]
          Zicntr Counters         ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░   0.4%  [~]
          Base   Scalar base                        36.5%
        
          Total instructions analyzed: 2,842
          ...
        ```
        
        ## Install
        
        ```bash
        # 1. Install QEMU user-mode emulation
        sudo apt install qemu-user
        
        # 2. Build the QEMU plugin
        make plugin
        
        # 3. Install the Python package
        pip install -e .
        
        # 4. Verify everything works
        riscv-xray check
        ```
        
        ## Usage
        
        ```bash
        # Profile a RISC-V binary
        riscv-xray profile ./my-binary
        
        # Profile with arguments
        riscv-xray profile ./my-binary --args "--config prod.yaml"
        
        # Output as JSON
        riscv-xray profile ./my-binary --output json
        
        # Output as HTML report
        riscv-xray profile ./my-binary --output html > report.html
        
        # Check dependencies
        riscv-xray check
        ```
        
        ## How It Works
        
        ```
        Your Binary
            |
            v
        qemu-riscv64 + xray_plugin.so   (captures every instruction mnemonic)
            |
            v
        classifier.py                    (maps mnemonics to RVA23 extensions)
            |
            v
        recommender.py                   (generates actionable suggestions)
            |
            v
        report.py                        (renders text / HTML / JSON output)
        ```
        
        ## Built On
        
        ### QEMU — https://www.qemu.org
        riscv-xray uses QEMU's TCG plugin API for user-mode RISC-V emulation. QEMU is the industry standard for RISC-V software development without hardware.
        
        ### riscv-application-profiler — https://github.com/mahendraVamshi/riscv-application-profiler
        When installed, riscv-xray uses riscv-application-profiler as its instruction analysis backend for deeper metrics. We strongly recommend installing it for best results:
        ```bash
        pip install riscv-application-profiler
        ```
        
        ### RAVE — https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.13639
        The RAVE research project (European Processor Initiative) demonstrated the QEMU TCG plugin approach for RISC-V instruction profiling. riscv-xray extends this concept to all RVA23 extensions with a developer-friendly layer.
        
        ---
        
        riscv-xray builds on top of QEMU, riscv-application-profiler, and concepts from the RAVE research project. Our contribution is the integration layer, RVA23 extension mapping, and developer-friendly output with actionable recommendations.
        
